input: What are some recent studies on neuron morphology in the cerebrum?
actual_output:
Here are some recent studies on neuron morphology in the cerebrum:

### 1. Key morphological features of human pyramidal neurons
- **Published:** May 14, 2024
- **Summary:** This study performed intracellular injections and 3D reconstructions of over 200 pyramidal neurons from human occipital primary visual area and associative temporal cortex. It found that pyramidal neurons in the temporal cortex are larger and more complex than those in primary sensory cortex, with more dendritic spines. The study also compared human neocortical neurons to hippocampal and mouse neurons, highlighting species-specific differences.
- **Link:** [PMC Article](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11094408/)

### 2. Neuronal diversity and stereotypy at multiple scales through whole brain morphometry
- **Published:** November 26, 2024
- **Summary:** This paper discusses neuronal diversity and stereotypy across the whole brain using morphometric analysis, providing insights into structural variations at multiple scales.
- **Link:** [PMC Article](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11599929/)

### 3. Of mice and men: Dendritic architecture differentiates human from mice neuronal networks
- **Published:** December 19, 2024
- **Authors:** Lida Kanari et al.
- **Summary:** This study compares dendritic architectures between human and mouse neuronal networks, revealing key differences that may underlie functional distinctions.
- **Link:** [BioRxiv Preprint](https://www.biorxiv.org/content/10.1101/2023.09.11.557170v3.full)

### 4. What makes human cortical pyramidal neurons functionally complex
- **Published:** December 17, 2024
- **Authors:** Ido Aizenbud et al.
- **Summary:** This research investigates the functional complexity of human cortical pyramidal neurons, linking morphological features to their computational properties.
- **Link:** [BioRxiv Preprint](https://www.biorxiv.org/content/10.1101/2024.12.17.628883v1.full)

### 5. Whole human-brain mapping of single cortical neurons for profiling
- **Published:** October 13, 2023
- **Author:** Hanchuan Peng
- **Summary:** The study introduces adaptive cell tomography (ACTomography) to map and quantify neuron morphology and distribution at the whole-brain scale in human cortical neurons.
- **Link:** [Science Advances Article](https://www.science.org/doi/10.1126/sciadv.adf3771)

If you want more details on any of these studies or additional papers, please let me know!

input: How can I simulate on the platform ?
actual_output:
To simulate on the Open Brain Platform, you can follow these general steps:

## 1. Choose the Type of Simulation
The platform supports different scales and types of simulations, including:
- Single neuron simulations
- Synaptome simulations
- Metabolism and NGV unit simulations (available as notebooks)
- Upcoming models: microcircuits, brain regions, brain systems, whole brain

## 2. Select or Create Models
You can either:
- Use existing models available on the platform (e.g., morphological electric models (ME-models), electrical models (e-models), ion channel models)
- Customize or create your own models by changing cellular composition or other parameters

## 3. Access Simulation Notebooks
- The platform provides downloadable notebooks for running simulations remotely.
- Soon, you will be able to run these notebooks directly on the platform.

## 4. Run Simulations
- Execute the simulation notebooks either locally or on the platform (when available).
- You can perform various analyses and experiments on the simulation results.

## 5. Analyze Results
- Use platform tools to analyze simulation outputs.
- Visualize neuron morphology, electrical activity, synaptic connections, etc.

---

If you want, I can guide you to specific simulation models or notebooks available on the platform or provide detailed instructions for a particular type of simulation. Would you like to explore available simulation models or notebooks now?
